{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568120"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19486"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19486"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.02,0.88,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85182"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12240"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69465"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"410"},{"type":"tags","id":"2431"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85182"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of a painless growing lesion on his lower lip. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a retired farmer and spends significant time outdoors. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a firm, irregular, ulcerated lesion on the vermillion border of his lower lip (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smoking","Immunosuppression","Sun exposure","Previous burn","Human immunodeficiency virus infection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a lesion highly suspicious for squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) of the lip. The clinical features - including the patient\u0027s age, outdoor occupation, and the appearance of a firm, irregular, ulcerated lesion on the lower lip - are typical for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESun exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary risk factor for lip SCC, particularly affecting the lower lip which receives more direct ultraviolet radiation. The cumulative effect of sun exposure over many years leads to DNA damage and subsequent malignant transformation of keratinocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmoking\u003C/strong\u003E is a risk factor for lip SCC, but is less significant than sun exposure. Smoking tends to affect both upper and lower lips equally, unlike sun exposure which predominantly affects the lower lip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmunosuppression\u003C/strong\u003E increases the risk of all skin cancers, including SCC, by reducing immune surveillance. However, this patient is not immunosuppressed, and sun exposure remains the more likely causative factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevious burn\u003C/strong\u003E injuries can lead to SCC development in burn scars (Marjolin\u0027s ulcer), but this typically occurs after many years and is not relevant to this presentation on the lip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E can increase the risk of SCC through immunosuppression, but this is a much less common scenario than sun-induced SCC, particularly in an elderly patient with significant sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma of the lip most commonly occurs due to cumulative sun exposure.","The lower lip is more commonly affected than the upper lip due to greater sun exposure.","Squamous cell carcinoma typically presents as a non-healing ulcer or growing mass on the lip."],"references":["Nokovitch L, Maquet C, Crampon F, et al. Oral Cavity Squamous Cell Carcinoma Risk Factors: State of the Art. J Clin Med. 2023;12(9):3264. Published 2023 May 3. doi:10.3390/jcm12093264"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69465"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19486"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21559"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21559"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yzKDacgvhKz6ensjoZUDMdwCr9XVVK.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yzKDacgvhKz6ensjoZUDMdwCr9XVVK.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":380}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69465"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-15T19:34:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-15T19:35:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12240"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85182"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"sel